-- 2 conversations, 4 questions each = 8 questions total

E'Woman: Hi, I''m here to discuss my course schedule for next semester.\nMan: Sure, have a seat. What are you thinking about?\nWoman: Well, I''d like to take organic chemistry, but I''m worried about the workload.\nMan: That''s a valid concern. Organic chemistry is one of the more demanding courses. How many credits are you taking now?\nWoman: Sixteen. And I''m also working part-time at the campus bookstore.\nMan: I''d recommend reducing your course load to fourteen credits if you take organic chemistry. That way you''ll have more time for the lab component.\nWoman: But wouldn''t that delay my graduation?\nMan: Not necessarily. You could take a summer course to make up the credits. Many students find that more manageable.\nWoman: That''s a good point. I hadn''t considered summer courses.\nMan: Also, I''d suggest joining the chemistry study group. Students who participate tend to perform significantly better.\nWoman: Where do I sign up for that?\nMan: I''ll send you the information by email. Check with the department office if you don''t hear from me by Friday.', TRUE),

('a0000001-0002-4000-8000-000000000002', 'B', 'Housing Office Visit', '',
E'Man: Good morning. I need to discuss a problem with my dormitory assignment.\nWoman: Of course. What seems to be the issue?\nMan: I was assigned to a triple room, but I specifically requested a double.\nWoman: Let me check your application. Yes, I see your preference was for a double room. Unfortunately, we had more applicants than double rooms available this year.\nMan: Is there any way to switch? The room is really too small for three people.\nWoman: We do have a waiting list for room changes. I can add your name to it.\nMan: How long does the wait usually take?\nWoman: It depends. Sometimes a spot opens up within a few weeks, but it could take the entire semester.\nMan: That''s frustrating. Are there any other options?\nWoman: Well, you could look into off-campus housing. We maintain a list of approved apartments near the university.\nMan: I''d rather stay on campus for the convenience. Please put me on the waiting list.\nWoman: Done. I''ll contact you as soon as something becomes available. In the meantime, I can arrange a meeting with your roommates and an RA to discuss room guidelines.', TRUE);



-- ── PART C: Talks / Lectures ─────────────────────────────────
-- 3 talks, 4 questions each = 12 questions total

E'Narrator: Listen to part of a lecture in an earth science class.\nProfessor: Today we''re going to discuss the water cycle, one of the most fundamental processes on our planet. The water cycle, also known as the hydrological cycle, describes the continuous movement of water on, above, and below the surface of the Earth.\nThe cycle begins with evaporation. The sun heats water in oceans, lakes, and rivers, causing it to evaporate into the atmosphere as water vapor. This process is responsible for moving about ninety percent of the water into the atmosphere.\nThe next stage is condensation. As water vapor rises, it cools and condenses around tiny particles in the atmosphere, forming clouds. These particles, called condensation nuclei, can be dust, pollen, or even pollution particles.\nWhen the water droplets in clouds become heavy enough, they fall back to Earth as precipitation — rain, snow, sleet, or hail. About seventy-five percent of this precipitation falls into the oceans.\nThe water that falls on land either runs off into rivers and streams, which eventually flow back to the ocean, or it seeps into the ground, becoming groundwater. Plants also absorb water through their roots and release it back into the atmosphere through a process called transpiration.\nThis cycle has been operating for billions of years and is essential for sustaining all life on Earth.', TRUE),

('a0000001-0003-4000-8000-000000000002', 'C', 'The Printing Press', '',
E'Narrator: Listen to part of a lecture in a history class.\nProfessor: I want to talk about one of the most transformative inventions in human history — the printing press. Johannes Gutenberg is generally credited with developing the first mechanical movable type printing system in Europe around fourteen forty.\nNow, it''s important to note that Gutenberg didn''t invent printing from scratch. The Chinese had been using woodblock printing for centuries, and Korea had developed metal movable type before Gutenberg. What Gutenberg did was combine several existing technologies — the screw press, movable type, oil-based ink, and a special metal alloy — into a practical, efficient system.\nThe impact was enormous. Before the printing press, books were copied by hand, primarily by monks in monasteries. A single book could take months to produce. Gutenberg''s press could produce hundreds of copies in the time it previously took to make one.\nThis dramatically reduced the cost of books and made knowledge accessible to a much wider audience. Literacy rates began to rise, and new ideas could spread faster than ever before. Many historians consider the printing press a key catalyst for the Renaissance, the Reformation, and eventually the Scientific Revolution.\nThe printing press essentially democratized knowledge. For the first time, information was not controlled exclusively by religious and political elites. This shift had profound implications for education, science, and governance that we still feel today.', TRUE),

('a0000001-0003-4000-8000-000000000003', 'C', 'Animal Migration', '',
E'Narrator: Listen to part of a lecture in a biology class.\nProfessor: Today I''d like to discuss animal migration, one of the most remarkable phenomena in the natural world. Migration is the seasonal movement of animals from one region to another, usually in response to changes in temperature, food availability, or breeding conditions.\nOne of the most well-known examples is the Arctic tern, which makes the longest migration of any animal. These birds fly from their breeding grounds in the Arctic to the Antarctic and back again each year — a round trip of about forty-four thousand miles. That means over its lifetime, an Arctic tern may fly the equivalent of three trips to the moon and back.\nBut how do animals navigate over such incredible distances? Research has identified several mechanisms. Many birds use the position of the sun and stars for orientation. Some species, like sea turtles and salmon, can detect the Earth''s magnetic field and use it as an internal compass.\nAnother fascinating example is the monarch butterfly. Monarchs migrate up to three thousand miles from Canada to central Mexico each fall. What''s remarkable is that no single butterfly makes the complete round trip. It takes three to four generations to complete the full cycle, yet each generation somehow knows exactly where to go.\nScientists believe this navigational ability may be encoded in their DNA, passed down through generations. Recent studies have identified a special protein in monarch butterfly antennae that is sensitive to the Earth''s magnetic field, which may help guide their journey.', TRUE);

